05636nam a22008295i 9781442689350DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222003onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426893507 a10.3138/97814426893502doi  a(DE-B1597)626565  a(OCoLC)1322124987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aZ286.S37bT54 2003eb 7aLAN0270002bisacsh04a808/.0204aThe Thesis and the Book :bA Guide for First-Time Academic Authors /ced. by Ian Montagnes, Eleanor Harman, Chris Bucci, Siobhan McMenemy. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Second Edition -- tPreface to the First Edition -- tContributors -- tChapter One The Thesis and the Book -- tChapter Two The Dissertation’s Deadly Sins -- tChapter Three Revising the Dissertation and Publishing the Book -- tChapter Four Avoiding the Warmed-Over Dissertation -- tChapter Five Thesis to Book: What to Get Rid of and What to Do with What Is Left -- tChapter Six An Academic Author’s Checklist -- tChapter Seven Basic Advice for Novice Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe academic caveat Publish or Perish is not a new one, and for over a quarter of a century, The Thesis and the Book has come to the aid of graduate students in their quest for publication. The doctoral dissertation, usually the first book-length study completed by a scholar, is, however, only rarely publishable as a book. Understanding the differences between the two forms is a crucial part of one's education as a scholar and is equally important in appreciating the endeavours of scholarly publishers. The Thesis and the Book: A Guide for First-Time Academic Authors, revised and expanded in this second edition, will continue to provide the best overview of the process of revising a dissertation for publication.Drawing on the expertise of the contributors, all of whom are editors, publishers, and scholars themselves, the chapters present the rudimentary differences between a thesis and a book (including matters of purpose and audience), give guidance on the necessary stylistic, technical, and structural revisions to the dissertation, and offer advice to first-time authors who must not only revise their work to satisfy prospective publishers, but also learn a good deal of the ins and outs of scholarly publishing.The Thesis and the Book will continue to be of great value to graduating doctoral students seeking publication and to the faculty members who supervise these students. It will also be of value to acquisitions editors at scholarly presses, who must contend with the submission of revised dissertations for publication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAcademic writing -- Handbooks, manuals, etc. 0aAuthorship -- Style manuals. 0aDissertations, Academic -- Handbooks, manuals, etc. 0aDissertations, Academic. 0aScholarly publishing -- Handbooks, manuals, etc. 0aScholarly publishing. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Publishing.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Robert Plant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucci, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDowling, William C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalpenny, Francess G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarman, Eleanor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolmes, Olive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMenemy, Siobhan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMontagnes, Ian, eeditor.4edt4h